Introduction¶

The purpose of this analysis is to demonstrate common statistical methods to analyze a data set using the python programming language. I will conduct some basic analysis of the variables and compare different methods that could be used with the goal of understanding relationships in the data. Understanding relationships in data can be very useful especially if the data is unfamiliar once there is an understanding of the cause and effect relationship of the data this information can be put to use for business planning to try to make affect a desirable outcome.

For this analysis, I have chosen to analyze housing data which most people are familiar with. The goal of this analysis to predict potential median values of homes in the Boston market. The Boston housing data comes from a 1978 census and contains 14 variables that can be used to analyze the data set.

When trying to determine real estate values a common approach is to use 'comps' or comparables of previous homes sold in nearby areas to determine the price of a home. Location is one of the primary factors that can predict the value of a home. Homes in desirable neighborhoods will generally sell for higher prices than less desirable neighborhoods a desirable neighborhood may have good schools, low crime, access to freeways, larger home size, and other amenities.

If we have a good data set then the data should reflect some of the common assumptions that are the foundations of the real estate market.

Real Estate Market Assumptions

  • Location matters.
  • Better locations will yield a higher home price.
  • Larger homes will yield a higher home price.
  • Close access to public transportation, freeways, employment locations, and other desirable places will fetch a higher price.
  • Low crime areas are more desirable than high crime areas

In this analysis, I will be looking to validate these assumptions and also looking to see which of these assumptions provides the strongest relationship with the target variable which is the median home price. I will also be keeping an eye for any unique relationships that are not as common or are not commonly recognized as impacting the median price of a home. Finally, I will build a linear regression model to predict the median home prices in the Boston market based on the dataset.

Correlation Methods¶

In order to find correlation among variables I will compare a few different methods for obtaining correlations. Since binary and categorical variables are representative data the numerical values should not be considered as continous numerical value.

  • Binary and continuous variable correlation - Point Biserial Method
  • Categorical and continuous variable correlation - Spearman Rank Correlation, Kendall's Tau Method
  • Continuous and continuous variable correlation - Pearson Corerlation Method

Note: Scipy Point Biserial method produces the same result as Pandas pearsonr method

The Normal Distribution¶

In [20]:
Image(url= "https://studiousguy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Normal-Distribution-curve.jpg")
Out[20]:

Skewness and kurtosis are the two primary measures of a normal distribution when it comes to the shape of the distribution. Skewness refers to how centered the data is and kurtosis refers to how tall or flat a data set is. The skewness and kurtosis can be measured mathematically to determine whether a dataset has a normal distribution.

Measuring Skewness and Kurtosis¶

  • If skewness is less an -1 or greater than 1 the distribution is highly skewed
  • If skewness is between -1 -1/2 or between 1/2 and 1 the distribution is moderately skewed.
  • If skewness is between -1/2 and 1/2, the distrubution is symmetric.
  • If kurtosis is $\approx$ 3 it is called mesokurtic and is considered to be a normal distribution.
  • If kurtosis is < 3 it is called platykurtic amd the distribution will appear very flat and broad.
  • if the kurtosis is > 3 it is called leptokurtic and the distribution will appear skinny and tall.
In [21]:

Reducing Skewness with Log Transformation¶

Here I will perform a log transformation to try reduce the skewness of the LSTAT variable then I will compare the impact it has on correlation and predictive quality of a linear regression model. The residuals should also be compared against both LSTAT and LSTAT_LOG to ensure that the $R^2$ scored is not being artificially increased without also reducing the residuals.

In [71]:
#creating a serparte variable for LSTAT with log transformation applied
LSTAT_LOG = np.log(features['LSTAT'] + 1)
In [75]:
print('LSTAT skewness without log transformation',skew(features['LSTAT']))
print('LSTAT skewness with log transformation',skew(LSTAT_LOG))

Split the data for supervised training¶

Linear regression is a supervised learning model. When training a model using a supervised model the data gets split into two data sets training and testing. The model is first trained on the training data then once the model is trained it can be tested on the test data. Supervised learning allows for the validation of the model because the test data can be compared against the actual data.

In [117]:
#Splitting LSTAT 
L_X_train,L_X_test,L_Y_train,L_Y_test = train_test_split(L_X,L_Y,random_state=1)
In [118]:
#Splitting LSTAT_LOG 
LL_X_train,LL_X_test,LL_Y_train,LL_Y_test = train_test_split(LL_X,LL_Y,random_state=1)

  • Null Hypothesis: There is no relationship between LSTAT_LOG and Median Value.

  • Alternative Hypothesis: The coefficiant $\neq$ 0 and there is a relationship between LSTAT_LOG and Median_Value.

Conclusion¶

In this analysis, the goal was to see if the Boston housing data reflects commonly held assumptions about general real estate market dynamics. Basic commonly held assumptions of any given real estate market are location matters, better locations will yield a higher home price than a less desirable location, larger homes will also yield a higher home price. Close access to transportation, employment, shopping centers, and other amenities will also yield a higher home price and low crime areas are more desirable than high crime areas.

Additionally, statistical concepts and measures were analyzed to determine the most important variables that contribute to the target variable median home price. The LSTAT variable had the highest predictive value. LSTAT which refers to the proportion of the population who would be considered as having a lower standard of living. Residents who might be characterized as having a lower standard of living would be individuals who have not completed high school or are considered laborers.

It stands to reason that these individuals would earn less money causing them not to be able to afford a home in a more desirable area. The data shows a clear negative correlation between LSTAT and Median Value, as the lower standard of living individuals increase in a geographic area median home values begin to decrease. The assumption regarding larger homes yields higher prices is also reflected by the data and in the second most important feature for determining median home value. The RM variable which refers to the number of rooms in home shows a positive correlation when the number of bedrooms increases the median home value also increases. The third assumption relating to nearby amenities such as transportation, employment, and shopping was represented by the DIS, RAD, and ZN variables.

The DIS variable refers to the weighted distance between the five employment centers in the Boston region, RAD refers to an index of quality and distance of highways and roadways and the ZN variable refers to the proportion of buildings zoned for greater than 25,000 square feet. These three variables had a much lower correlation than anticipated. The ZN variable had a very low correlation, but it is easy to see due to the vagueness of the variable buildings zoned with greater than 25,000 square could be retail, commercial or industrial zones which may have differing impacts on median home value.
One surprise finding was the importance the pupil to teacher ratio PTRATIO has on determining median home value. This relationship does not appear to have a linear relationship so another model that can handle non-linear relationships might be more useful in determining the validity of this relationship.

Finally, a transformation on the LSTAT variable was performed to reduce the skewness to see if this would have a positive impact on the LSTAT variable. The LSTAT variable without transformation produced an $R^2$ score of 0.53 however when a log transformation was performed it increased the $R^2$ value to 0.65. The residuals of LSTAT and LSTAT_LOG were compared and LSTAT_LOG showed a reduction in the overall error rate which validates the fact that performing a log transformation on the LSTAT variable increased the predictive value while also reducing the error rate.
